<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">exhibited the truly romantic Scene.  When the vapours rise suddenly from the Hills and are dissipated in air a Storm is shortly expected, but when they descend, warm and calm weather is generally the result of the chymical process.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Portage river is three leagues from the bottom of the bay and in clear weather is distinguished from the eastern shore.  The traverse is allowed to be three leagues and is never safe with either a Southerly wind as the first may blow you into the lake and the last sends in a swell often two heavy for loaded canoes.  I have some reluctance in relating an accident which twice happened to my watch nearly in the middle of this traverse as it appears to have Something of the marvellous in it.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[H]</span>owever so it <span class="DelHand-author">has</span> <span class="AddHand-author">is</span>, that in June 1792 I took it from my pocket to see the hour, and it became instantly deranged running down the whole chain in less than a minute.  I sent it down to Montreal and got it up the ensuing year and it again played me the same prank in the same place; now whether this was merely accident or owing to some powerful Magnetic</p>

